04128nam a22006495i 9780813553924DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112011nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135539247 a10.36019/97808135539242doi  a(DE-B1597)529162  a(OCoLC)778339948  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aPN1995.9.F54 7aPER0000002bisacsh1 aMiklitsch, Robert, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSiren City :bSound and Source Music in Classic American Noir /cRobert Miklitsch. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2011] 4cÂ©2011  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b24 illustrations.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreview -- tCredits -- tIntroduction: Sound and (Source) Music -- tPrologue: Small World, Big Sign -- t1. House Sound: Reverb, Offscreen Sound, and Voice-Over Narration in Early RKO Noir -- t2. Sonic Effects: Sound and Fury in Forties Noir -- t3. Audio Technologies: Intercoms and Dictaphones, Telephones and Radios, Phonographs and Jukeboxes -- t4. Blues in the Night: Popular and Classical Instrumental Source Music -- t5. Singing Detectives and Bluesmen, Black Jazzwomen and Torch Singers -- t6. The Big Number (Side B): Killing Them Softly -- t7. The Big Number (A Side): Siren City -- tEpilogue: Silences -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aHailed for its dramatic expressionist visuals, film noir is one of the most prominent genres in Hollywood cinema. Yet, despite the "boom" in sound studies, the role of sonic effects and source music in classic American noir has not received the attention it deserves. Siren City engagingly illustrates how sound tracks in 1940s film noir are often just as compelling as the genre's vaunted graphics. Focusing on a wide range of celebrated and less well known films and offering an introductory discussion of film sound, Robert Miklitsch mobilizes the notion of audiovisuality to investigate period sound technologies such as the radio and jukebox, phonograph and Dictaphone, popular American music such as "hot" black jazz, and "big numbers" featuring iconic performers such as Lauren Bacall, Veronica Lake, and Rita Hayworth. Siren City resonates with the sounds and source music of classic American noir-gunshots and sirens, swing riffs and canaries. Along with the proverbial private eye and femme fatale, these audiovisuals are central to the noir aesthetic and one important reason the genre reverberates with audiences around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978081355392440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813553924423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813553924.jpg  a978-3-11-068861-0  Rutgers University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK